Don’t know where you are from, but two major things come to mind.
Thing 1: (Inherent in remote places) A helpful person is treated like neighbor or friend. That is, a total stranger that happens by and helps pull someone out of the ice will not quickly be forgotten. Some parts of Alaska they say are 100 years in the past, and I remember watching a documentary about daily life there. This one village’s public safety officer spoke frankly about fatalities in that village.

>Here’s so-and-so’s grave. He was helping dock a fishing boat and fell in the water and got trapped under the ice.

>Here is the marker for these three hunters. They went out on an overnight hunting trip via snowmobile, but the weather turned... On day 4 of what had become a really bad storm we heard from them briefly by satellite phone, said one had taken a bad fall, but the storm unexpectedly lasted another 6 days and we never found any trace of them.

Crazy shit like that, and this was from 2008 or so. Note that these people weren’t morons completely unaware of the risks or lacked modern technology, but people that were born in the same village their grandparents were born in, went to school elsewhere, and had (limited) access to the internet. Some villages had moved, merged, or vanished because the young people left, but it was very old-school events (so and so died of dysentery because the person getting the medicine was killed by wolves) happening to modern people.

Mia and Anon helping someone in that environment isn’t something an outsider can show up and make the people forget.

*For the curious, I’ll try to find a link, but if you watch Alaska State Troopers or that Vice docu on the Alaskan guy with a remote cabin, you start to see why a helpful stranger would quickly gain acceptance.
